\begin_layout Standard
There is one SPNE such that 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 plays 
\begin_inset Formula $R.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider now SPNE such that 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 plays 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $M.$
\end_inset

 Denote the beliefs of 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(R),$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(L),$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(M),$
\end_inset

 i.e.
 2, when it comes its turn to play, believes 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 played 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(R).$
\end_inset

 Obviously, when it comes for 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 to play, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(R)=0.$
\end_inset

 The expected payoff to 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 of playing 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(L),$
\end_inset

 and of playing 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(M).$
\end_inset

 Therefore,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(L)>\mu(M),$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 plays 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 and then 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 is better off playing 
\begin_inset Formula $L.$
\end_inset

 By backward induction, under those beliefs, 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 will indeed play 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 since this gets it 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

 rather than 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 if it played 
\begin_inset Formula $R,$
\end_inset

 so there is a sustainable belief such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(L)=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(l)=1.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(L)<\mu(M),$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 plays 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 is indifferent between playing 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 since both get it payoff 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

.
 But then, by backward induction, 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 is better off playing 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 so the belief that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(R)=0$
\end_inset

 is not sustainable.
 We can thus eliminate the possibility that a belief such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(R)=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(L)<\mu(M)$
\end_inset

 could be sustained under a SPNE.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(L)=\mu(M)=\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 is indifferent between playing 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $r.$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 must be indifferent between playing 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 so I must have 
\begin_inset Formula $3\mu(l)=\mu(l),$
